SIMPLE: tie
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tie
<hw>Tie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Ties</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[AS. <ets>t⟦emac⟧ge</ets>,
<ets>t<?/ge</ets>, <ets>t⟦imac⟧ge</ets>. ⟦root⟧64. See <er>Tie</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A knot; a fastening.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bond; an obligation, moral or legal; <as>as, the
sacred <ex>ties</ex> of friendship or of duty; the <ex>ties</ex> of
allegiance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No distance breaks the <qex>tie</qex> of blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A knot of hair, as at the back of a wig.</def>
<rj><au>Young.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An equality in numbers, as of votes, scores, etc.,
which prevents either party from being victorious; equality in any
contest, as a race.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch. & Engin.)</fld> <def>A beam or rod for
holding two parts together; in railways, one of the transverse timbers
which support the track and keep it in place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A line, usually straight, drawn
across the stems of notes, or a curved line written over or under the
notes, signifying that they are to be slurred, or closely united in the
performance, or that two notes of the same pitch are to be sounded as
one; a bind; a ligature.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Low shoes fastened with
lacings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bale tie</b></col>, <cd>a fastening for the ends of a
hoop for a bale.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tie</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tie
<hw>Tie</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> (<mark>Obs</mark>. <conjf>Tight</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Tying</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>ti<?/en</ets>, <ets>teyen</ets>,
AS. <ets>t⟦imac⟧gan</ets>, <ets>ti⟦eacute⟧gan</ets>, fr.
<ets>te⟦aacute⟧g</ets>, <ets>te⟦aacute⟧h</ets>, a rope; akin to Icel.
<ets>taug</ets>, and AS. <ets>te⟦oacute⟧n</ets> to draw, to pull. See
<er>Tug</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf. <er>Tow</er> to drag.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To fasten with a band or cord and knot; to bind.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Tie</xex> the kine to the cart.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>1 Sam. vi.
7.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My son, keep thy father's commandment, and forsake not the law of
thy mother: bind them continually upon thine heart, and <qex>tie</qex>
them about thy neck.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. vi. 20,21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form, as a knot, by interlacing or complicating a
cord; also, to interlace, or form a knot in; <as>as, to <ex>tie</ex> a
cord to a tree</as>; to knit; to knot.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧We do not
<xex>tie</xex> this knot with an intention to puzzle the
argument.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp. Burnet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To unite firmly; to fasten; to hold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In bond of virtuous love together <qex>tied</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hold or constrain by authority or moral
influence, as by knotted cords; to oblige; to constrain; to restrain; to
confine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not <qex>tied</qex> to rules of policy, you find⟦br⟧
Revenge less sweet than a forgiving mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To unite, as notes, by a cross
line, or by a curved line, or slur, drawn over or under them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To make an equal score with, in a contest; to be
even with.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To ride and tie</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Ride</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To tie down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To fasten so as to prevent from rising.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
restrain; to confine; to hinder from action.</cd> -- <col><b>To tie
up</b></col>, <cd>to confine; to restrain; to hinder from motion or
action.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tie</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tie
<hw>Tie</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a tie; to make an equal
score.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tiebar</ent>⟦br⟧
